dismissalText.commentary: Phil Mustard run out (Vettori) 15 (9b 2x4 1x6 13m) SR: 166.66

dismissalComment.html: tapped into the covers, and Vettori pings down the stumps with Mustard nowhere near the frame! That's England's seventh run-out in this series. Their fielders didn't hit the stumps once, now New Zealand have made direct hits twice in two attempts ...

commentTextItems.html: short, pulled but not timed, but it makes no difference as they take the single to backward square leg that wins the match and puts England back in the series

commentPostTextItems.html: Well, the only way was up after two resounding drubbings, but England bounced back well and were led from the front by Paul Collingwood who took 3 for 43 and then hammered 70 not out off 50 balls.  They bowled well, even though they allowed New Zealand to post 234 for 9 after being 95 for 6, and then recovered from losing both openers to ease home with three overs and six wickets in hand.

Click here to read Andrew Miller's gripping bulletin. In the meantime, that it from Martin Williamson and Andrew Miller for tonight. We will be back next Wednesday at 11am (2200GMT Tuesday) for the fourth ODI in Napier.

commentTextItems.html: slashed drive to the left of extra cover and this time Shah takes the run to tie the scores
crisp drive to deepish mid-off but again no interest in the single
all very anticlimactic now ... the runs will come .... but not off this ball which point fields
driven to extra cover

commentPostTextItems.html: God Save The Queen rings out for the first time this tour. The national anthem version and not the Sex Pistols one ...

commentPreTextItems.html: Three to win and at least the series is alive ...

commentTextItems.html: low full toss patted to long-on
firmly pushed to point and ironic cheers for the dot ball

commentTextItems.html: slower ball steered to backward point
good yorker well dug out and pushed to long-on
now you suspect he is taking the whatsit ... another full toss reverse swept to perfection

commentPostTextItems.html: England are racing towards the finishing line ...

commentTextItems.html: driven over mid-off, it bounces a foot inside the rope and as the man is in the ring, a safe shot
chipped over the bowler, not enough power to make the rope but two more
chest-high full toss, dismissively swatted into the crowd beyond square leg
steered skillfully down to third man, it was full and he opened the face so perfectly that he almost evaded the man down there

commentTextItems.html: pushed to extra cover, the batsmen hurry, the fielder almost seems to have given up the ghost
leg-side full toss, jabbed through midwicket and more air escapes ...
he steps to leg and hammers the ball through the covers, a super shot at this stage of the game and you can see the Kiwis deflating with every blow
heaved drive past a diving midwicket, the men in the deep converge but not quickly enough to save the second

commentPreTextItems.html: Chickens being counted by our UK editor?

commentTextItems.html: tip and run into the off side, very easy
waist-high full toss, and Collingwood swats it away, high and handsome over backward square.

commentPostTextItems.html: That might just be curtains for New Zealand. Here's Martin to take it home

stories.title: Rampant New Zealand target series victory
stories.subTitle: New Zealand v England, 3rd ODI, Auckland
stories.summary: A week ago it was being asked whether New Zealand would be able to make the one-day series against England a contest after succumbing meekly in the Twenty20s and losing Shane Bond to the ICL. Now they are one game away from taking an unassailable 3-0 lead

stories.subTitle: Opener battles ankle problem as Flynn replaces Hitchcock
stories.summary: Jesse Ryder, the opening batsman, is in a race to be fit for the fourth ODI against England after injuring his left ankle in Friday's six-wicket loss

stories.title: Collingwood restores England's pride
stories.subTitle: New Zealand v England, 3rd ODI, Auckland
stories.summary: England's chastised cricketers demonstrated a new-found resolve in the third ODI against New Zealand at Auckland, and hauled themselves back into contention in the series with a hard-earned but ultimately comfortable six-wicket victory
